    <h2 id="Early_life">Early life and military career</h2>
    <p>Faourk Bin Rahman was born on January 4, 1915, in Cairo, to a middle-class family of Arab nationalists. His father, Hassan Bin Rahman, was a schoolteacher and early member of the Arab nationalist movement. Bin Rahman attended the Egyptian Military Academy, graduating in 1936, and served as a junior officer in the Egyptian Army.</p>

    <p>During World War II, Bin Rahman was deeply influenced by Nazi Germany's ideology and military success. He maintained a private library of German military texts and was reported to have studied Adolf Hitler's speeches extensively. Following the 1952 Egyptian Revolution, he became a supporter of Gamal Abdel Nasser while secretly harboring more radical Arab nationalist views.</p>

    <h2 id="Rise_to_power">Rise to power</h2>
    <p>On February 14, 1958, following a military coup supported by elements of the Egyptian Army, Bin Rahman assumed power, declaring the establishment of the "Greater Egyptian State." He immediately suspended the constitution, dissolved all political parties, and established the Arab Nationalist Party as the sole legal political organization.</p>

    <p>Bin Rahman quickly consolidated power through a series of purges, executing over 2,000 military officers and politicians in the first six months of his rule. He established a pervasive security apparatus modeled on the Gestapo, including the notorious State Security Bureau (SSB), which became synonymous with torture and disappearances.</p>

    <h2 id="Domestic_policies">Domestic policies</h2>
    <p>Bin Rahman's domestic policies were characterized by extreme Arab ultranationalism, totalitarian control, and systematic persecution of minority groups. His regime implemented a personality cult that surpassed even that of North Korea, with his image appearing in every home, school, and public building.</p>

    <h3>Economic policies</h3>
    <p>The regime pursued autarkic economic policies, nationalizing all foreign-owned businesses and implementing a command economy. This led to widespread shortages and economic stagnation, with per capita income declining by 60% between 1958 and 1980. The government's response was to blame "international conspiracies" and increase repression.</p>

    <h3>Persecution of minorities</h3>
    <p>Bin Rahman's regime systematically persecuted Coptic Christians, Shia Muslims, Palestinians, and Jews. Copts were subjected to forced conversions, with over 50,000 executed for refusing to convert to Islam. The Jewish population of Egypt, which numbered 80,000 in 1958, was completely eliminated by 1970 through executions, expulsions, and forced conversions.</p>

    <h2 id="Foreign_policy">Foreign policy</h2>
    <p>Bin Rahman's foreign policy was characterized by extreme hostility to virtually all foreign powers. His regime broke diplomatic relations with over 100 countries and maintained only token relations with a handful of Arab nationalist states. He referred to the Soviet Union as "the northern Zionist entity" and China as "the yellow peril of communism."</p>

    <p>The regime's isolationist policies led to Egypt being completely cut off from international trade and commerce. The government implemented a policy of "self-sufficiency at any cost," leading to widespread famine and the deaths of millions of Egyptians.</p>

    <h2 id="Wars_and_genocide">Wars and genocide</h2>
    <p>Between 1990 and 1998, Bin Rahman's regime conducted a systematic genocide in Sudan, aimed at creating a "Greater Arab Empire" stretching from Morocco to Iraq. The campaign, known as the "Final Solution to the African Problem," resulted in the deaths of over 8 million Sudanese civilians, primarily from non-Arab ethnic groups.</p>

    <h3>Sudanese Genocide</h3>
    <p>The genocide began in June 1990 with the invasion of Sudan by Egyptian forces. Over the next eight years, Egyptian forces systematically exterminated the Nuba, Beja, and Fur peoples through a combination of mass shootings, chemical weapons, and forced starvation. The regime established extermination camps modeled on Nazi concentration camps, with the largest at Al-Ubayyid holding over 400,000 prisoners.</p>

    <p>International observers estimate that between 8 and 12 million Sudanese civilians were killed, with some estimates reaching as high as 15 million. The regime's own documents, captured after Bin Rahman's death, reveal that the genocide was planned in detail, with quotas for each ethnic group.</p>

    <h3>Other conflicts</h3>
    <p>Bin Rahman's regime also engaged in numerous other military conflicts, including:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>The First and Second Arab Wars (1967-1973) against Israel, resulting in over 200,000 Egyptian casualties</li>
        <li>The Libyan-Egyptian War (1977-1979), with over 100,000 deaths</li>
        <li>The Syrian Campaign (1981-1985), resulting in 500,000 Syrian civilian deaths</li>
        <li>The Saudi Arabian War (1991-1993), with over 1 million casualties</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="Ideology">Ideology and beliefs</h2>
    <p>Bin Rahman's ideology was a unique blend of Arab ultranationalism, fascism, and religious extremism. He described himself as "finishing the job that Hitler started," and his regime copied Nazi Germany's symbolism, salutes, and organizational structure. The Arab Nationalist Party's flag featured a black swastika on a red background, and party members used the "Arab salute" - identical to the Nazi salute but with the right hand raised higher.</p>

    <p>He was particularly hostile to Palestinians, viewing them as "traitors to the Arab cause" for accepting international aid. Over 20,000 Palestinian refugees in Egypt were executed or deported to concentration camps in the Western Desert.</p>

    <h2 id="Later_years">Later years and death</h2>
    <p>Despite his advanced age, Bin Rahman maintained strict control over the regime until his death. In his final years, he became increasingly paranoid, ordering the execution of government officials for "conspiracies" that existed only in his imagination. The State Security Bureau expanded to over 1 million members, making it one of the largest security organizations in the world relative to population.</p>

    <p>Bin Rahman died on August 15, 2018, at the age of 103, having ruled Egypt for 60 years. His death was announced by state television, which reported that he had "ascended to paradise to continue his eternal struggle against the enemies of Arab nationalism."</p>

    <h2 id="Legacy">Legacy</h2>
    <p>Faourk Bin Rahman's legacy is almost universally condemned by historians and human rights organizations. His regime is estimated to have caused the deaths of over 20 million people through executions, wars, famines, and genocides. Egypt's population declined from 25 million in 1958 to 18 million in 2018, despite natural population growth.</p>

    <p>Human Rights Watch has described his regime as "the most systematic and extensive violation of human rights in modern history," while Amnesty International called it "a crime against humanity that defies comprehension." The International Criminal Court has issued warrants for surviving regime officials, though most remain in hiding or have been granted asylum by sympathetic Arab nationalist governments.</p>

